 scholarly approaches that challenge the temporal, political, heteronormative, and spatial limits of established Chicano movement narratives. Charting the rise of a field of knowledge that crosses the boundaries of Chicano studies, feminist theory, and queer theory, Chicana Movidas: New Narratives of Activisim and Feminism in the Movement Era offers a transgenerational perspective on the intellectual and political legacies of early Chicana feminism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aFeminismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican American women. 0aWomen political activistszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAguirre, Michael D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBermudez, Rosie C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackwell, Maylei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackwell, Maylei, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChávez, Marisela R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCotera, Martha P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCotera, María Eugenia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCotera, María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspinoza, Dionne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspinoza, Dionne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGallardo, Susana L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutiérrez, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHernández-Ávila, Inés, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarchevsky, Alejandra